1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4.
Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 {The starting position of our repertoire. In this chapter
we will have a look at a number of sidelines.} 6. g3 (6. Bg5 Bb4 7. Ndb5 (7.
Nxc6 bxc6 8. e5 $2 {is met by} Qa5 $1 9. exf6 Qxg5 10. fxg7 Qxg7 $17) 7... h6
8. Bxf6 (8. Nd6+ Ke7 {is harmless.}) 8... Qxf6 9. a3 (9. Nc7+ $2 {runs into}
Kd8 10. Nxa8 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Qxc3+ 12. Ke2 (12. Qd2 Qxa1+) 12... Nd4+ {and
White has to give the queen.}) 9... Bc5 10. Qd2 O-O 11. f4 {Lukasiewicz-Graf,
Lyon 1995} d6 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Ya7a6] and the knight on b5 is in trouble.}) (6.
f3 $6 Bb4 7. Be3 d5 8. Bb5 Qc7 9. O-O O-O 10. Nde2 $2 (10. exd5 Bxc3 (10...
exd5 $15 {[%csl Rf3] is also possible.}) 11. dxc6 Bxb2 12. Rb1 Nd5 13. cxb7
Bxb7 14. Qd3 Nxe3 15. Qxe3 Bc3 $17 {Muhren-Peng, Leeuwarden 2005.}) 10... dxe4
11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. fxe4 Rd8 13. Bd3 Ne5 $17 {[%cal Yb4c5,Yc8b7,Yb7b6]
Feygin-Reinderman, Germany 2006.}) (6. Bf4 Bc5 (6... d6 7. Nxc6 (7. Ndb5 e5 8.
Bg5 {transposes to the Main Lines of the Sveshnikov.}) 7... bxc6 8. e5 $5 {
is likely to be White's idea of 6.Bf4.} Nd5 9. Nxd5 cxd5 {with reasonable play
for Black.}) ({An interesting line is} 6... Bb4 7. Ndb5 Nxe4 {which is usually
reached by the move-order 6.Ndb5 Bb4 7.Bf4.} (7... O-O 8. Bc7 Qe7 9. Bd6 Bxd6
10. Qxd6 Qd8 {leads to the Main Line of 6.Ndb5 Bc5 which will be discussed in
Chapter 5.}) 8. Qf3 d5 9. Nc7+ Kf8 10. Nxa8 e5 11. Bd2 Nd4 (11... Nxd2 $2 {
fails to} 12. Qxd5 $1 Nxf1 13. Qxd8+ Nxd8 14. O-O-O $18 {Kononenko-Westerberg,
Pardubice 2015.}) 12. Qd1 Qh4 $1 (12... Bg4 $2 13. Qc1 Nxd2 14. Qxd2 Qxa8 15.
a3 Ba5 16. b4 Bd8 {was played in Kosteniuk-Savina, Asnieres sur Seine 2018,
but now} 17. Nxd5 $16 {, followed by 18.Ne3 gives White a big advantage.}) 13.
g3 Qf6 14. Nxe4 Nf3+ 15. Ke2 (15. Qxf3 Qxf3 16. Bxb4+ Kg8 17. Nd6 Qxh1 18.
O-O-O Be6 19. Nc7) 15... Nd4+ 16. Ke1 Nf3+ 17. Ke2 Nd4+ 18. Ke1 Nf3+ 19. Ke2
Nd4+ {½-½ Gukesh-Dreev, Douglas 2019.}) 7. Ndb5 {directly leads to the lines
discussed in Chapter 5.}) 6... Bb4 7. Bg2 O-O ({Against the fianchetto setup,
I'm not a big fan of opening the centre with ...d7-d5 as it opens the diagonal
for the bishop. In case of} 7... d5 $6 8. exd5 Nxd5 {White could consider} 9.
O-O $5 {which gives him a dangerous initiative.} Bxc3 (9... Nxc3 10. Nxc6 (10.
bxc3 Bxc3 11. Nxc6 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Bd7 13. Rb1 Bxc6 14. Bxc6+ bxc6 15. Ba3 a5 16.
Rb7 Bb4 $11 {Schubert-Dolmatov, Groningen 1977.}) 10... bxc6 (10... Nxd1 11.
Nxd8 Kxd8 12. Rxd1+ $16) (10... Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Nxd1 12. Nxb4 O-O 13. Kf1 $16 {
[%csl Rd1]}) 11. bxc3 Bxc3 12. Bxc6+ Bd7 13. Qf3 Rc8 (13... Bxa1 14. Bxd7+ Qxd7
15. Qxa8+) 14. Qxc3 Bxc6 15. Qxg7 Qd5 16. f3 Qc5+ 17. Rf2 Qf8 18. Qd4 Rd8 19.
Qc3 Rd1+ 20. Kg2 {1-0 Glek-Maksimenko, Varna 1989.}) (9... O-O 10. Nxd5 exd5
11. c3 $16 {[%cal Yc1e3]}) 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. bxc3 {gives White excellent play
in Maze-Lobron, Germany 2016.}) 8. O-O d6 {Various other moves have been tried
here as well, but the text is the simplest.} (8... Bxc3 9. bxc3 d5 10. exd5
exd5 11. Bg5 h6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Rb1 Rd8 {and I think White is a bit better,
though it's very close to equality in Morovic Fernandez-Illescas Cordoba, Leon
1993}) (8... h6 9. Nxc6 $1 (9. a3 $6 Bxc3 10. bxc3 Qa5 11. a4 d5 12. exd5 exd5
13. Ba3 Re8 $132 {Guseinov-Kovalenko, Riga 2019.}) 9... bxc6 (9... dxc6 10. e5
Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Nd5 12. Ne4 $16 {Garcia Pantoja-Garcia Fuentes, Havana 2010.})
10. e5 {favors White, as} Nd5 $2 {fails to} 11. Nxd5 cxd5 12. Qg4 $16 {[%csl
Rb4,Rh6]}) 9. Nde2 (9. a4 {was recently seen in a high-profile game, but I
would suggest Black proceed with} e5 $5 (9... Rb8 10. Ncb5 Nxd4 {was seen
in Motylev-Dreev, Izhevsk 2019, but here White is recommended to recapture with
} 11. Qxd4 Bc5 12. Qd2 a6 13. b4 $1 {and White seizes the initiative on the
queenside.}) (9... Nxd4 10. Qxd4 Bc5 11. Qd3 Bd7 12. Be3 Bxe3 13. Qxe3 Qc7 {
is also about equal.}) 10. Nf5 Bxf5 11. exf5 Bxc3 12. bxc3 h6 $132 {is worth
investigating and could possibly lead to sharp play once White starts pushing
his g-pawn. Black is solid, however, and with moves like Re8 and e4 he should
be able to handle it.}) 9... a6 ({Also possible is} 9... h6 10. h3 a6 11. Be3
Qc7 12. Qd2 Rd8 13. Rfd1 b5 14. a3 Ba5 15. Bxh6 gxh6 16. e5 Ne8 17. exd6 Rxd6
18. Qxh6 Bb7 19. Qg5+ Kf8 20. Qh6+ Kg8 21. Qg5+ Kf8 22. Qh6+ {½-½
Barski-Cornette, Caleta 2019.}) 10. h3 Bc5 11. Bf4 (11. g4 Qc7 12. a4 b6 13. g5
Nd7 14. Nf4 Nde5 15. Nd3 Bb7 16. Nxc5 dxc5 {and Black is alright in
Baklan-Krasenkow, Koge 2014.}) 11... Ne5 12. g4 b5 {[%cal Yc8b7,Ya8c8] with
excellent play for Black in Petersen-Vocaturo, Helsingor 2019.} *

