1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4.
Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Be3 Bb4 7. Bd3 (7. f3 $6 d5 {transposes to 6.f3,
discussed in the previous chapter.}) (7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. Bd3 (8. a3 Bxc3+ (8...
Ba5 $5) 9. bxc3 Nxe4 (9... Qa5 10. Qd4 c5 11. Qxc5 Qxc5 12. Bxc5 Nxe4 13. Bd4
O-O 14. f3 $14 {Bacallao Alonso-Ortega Amarelle, Varadero 2016.}) 10. Qg4 Qf6
11. Bd4 Qg6 12. Qxg6 hxg6 13. Bxg7 Rh7 14. Bd4 d6 $15 {[%cal Ye6e5,Yf7f5]}) (8.
e5 $6 Nd5 9. Bd2 (9. Qg4 {is best answered by} Qa5 $1) 9... Qc7 10. f4 (10.
Nxd5 Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2 cxd5 12. f4 O-O $15 {gives Black excellent chances.}) 10...
Qb6 11. Qf3 O-O (11... Ba6 $5 $132 {exchanging off the bad bishop I also quite
like for Black.}) 12. a3 Bxc3 13. bxc3 Ba6 14. Bxa6 Qxa6 15. Qd3 {with
equality in Spassky-Huebner, Tilburg 1981.}) 8... d5 {see 7.Bd3}) (7. Be2 $2
Nxe4 {just loses an important central pawn, without any compensation.}) (7.
Ndb5 $2 Nxe4 {is also senseless.}) 7... d5 8. Nxc6 (8. exd5 Nxd5 9. Nxc6 bxc6 (
{Also possible is} 9... Nxe3 10. Nxd8 (10. fxe3 bxc6) 10... Nxd1 11. Rxd1 Kxd8
12. Bxh7+ Ke7 $44 {and Black obtains good play for the pawn.}) 10. Bd2 (10. O-O
Nxe3 (10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bxc3 12. Rb1 {gives White excellent compensation for
the pawn.}) 11. fxe3) (10. Bd4 Nxc3 11. Bxc3 (11. bxc3 $2 Qxd4 $1) 11... Bxc3+
12. bxc3 {is about equal, but I would rather be Black, because of a favourable
pawn structure.}) 10... O-O {with about equal chances.}) 8... bxc6 9. e5 {
and here Black has two options, a solid one and a more dynamical one.} Nd7 (
9... d4 10. exf6 (10. Bd2 Nd7 $1 11. Ne4 Bxd2+ 12. Qxd2 Nxe5 $17) 10... dxe3
11. fxg7 exf2+ 12. Kf1 (12. Kxf2 Qd4+ 13. Kf1 Qxg7 $17) 12... Rg8 13. Qg4 (13.
Bxh7 Rxg7 14. Qxd8+ Kxd8 15. Bd3 f5 {gives Black the initiative in
Plenca-Martinovic, Trieste 2016.}) 13... Bxc3 14. bxc3 Qf6 15. Qc4 Bd7 (15...
e5 $5) 16. Be4 e5 17. Bf3 Rxg7 18. Rd1 {was seen in Hector-Sax, Vejle 1994 and
now} Rc8 $5 19. Kxf2 Be6 {[%cal Ye6d5,Yg7g4] is fine for Black.}) 10. Qg4 Bf8 (
10... g6 $2 11. Qxb4 $18) 11. f4 (11. Qg3 Rb8 $5 12. b3 $6 h5 13. h4 {was seen
in Lucaroni-Khenkin, Bratto 2004 and now} d4 $3 14. Bxd4 Qa5 {intending 15...
c5 and Black seizes the initiative.}) 11... Rb8 12. Nd1 Qa5+ 13. Bd2 Qb6 14.
Qg3 Nc5 15. b3 Nxd3+ 16. cxd3 Ba6 {is perfectly fine for Black in
Mitkov-Illescas Cordoba, Ponferrada 1997.} *

