1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4.
Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Be2 Bb4 ({The most ambitious and principled move.
Another option is} 6... d6 {which leads to the Scheveningen structures, but
that's not our plan with this specific repertoire.}) 7. O-O (7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. e5
(8. Qd4 Qb6 $1) (8. O-O d5) 8... Ne4 (8... Nd5 $5 {is also possible.}) 9. Qd4 (
9. Bd2 Nxd2 10. Qxd2 Qa5 $15 {Daianu-Doncea, Bucharest 2007.}) 9... Qa5 $1 10.
a3 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Nxc3 12. Bf3 Nb1+ $1 (12... Nb5+ 13. Qb4 Qxb4+ 14. axb4 $14 {
Gu-Lintchevski, St Petersburg 2009.}) 13. Kd1 Nc3+ 14. Ke1 c5 15. Qd2 Rb8 $17)
(7. f3 $6 d5 $1) 7... Bxc3 ({Taking the pawn is the principled continuation.
Inferior, in my opinion, is} 7... O-O $6 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. e5 $1 {with similar
structure as in the main lines, but the main difference is that White's king
is now safe on the kingside. In the recent game Chigaev-Rakotomaharo, Douglas
2019 Black quickly got in trouble.}) 8. bxc3 Nxe4 {The absence of Black's
dark-squared bishop certainly gives White some compensation for the pawn,
since the black king is still in the centre. White has a couple of interesting
options, though objectively speaking Black should be able to neutralize the
initiative with correct play.} 9. Qd3 (9. Bf3 {is best met by} d5 $1 10. Bxe4 (
10. Nxc6 bxc6 {0-1 (35) Petrov,D (2215)-Kulaots,K (2573) Viljandi 2017}) 10...
dxe4 11. Ba3 (11. Qg4 $6 O-O 12. Qxe4 Bd7 $15 {is just better for Black in
Pliester-Michiels, Netherlands 2011 in view of the isolated doubled pawns on
the c-file.}) 11... Nxd4 12. cxd4 Qa5 13. Qc1 (13. Bd6 Qd5 14. Ba3 {initiates
a repetition.}) 13... Bd7 (13... f6 14. Re1 Bd7 15. Rxe4 Kf7 {and Black is OK
in Ponomariov-Eljanov, Kiev 2012.}) 14. Rb1 (14. c4 Bc6 15. d5 exd5 16. cxd5
Qxd5 17. Rd1 Qe5 $15 {[%cal Yf7f6,Ye8f7]}) 14... Bc6 15. c4 f6 16. Rd1 Rd8 $15
{[%cal Ye8f7]} 17. d5 $2 {Black is well-prepared for this central break.} exd5
18. Bb4 Qxa2 19. Qf4 Kf7 20. cxd5 Rxd5 21. Qc7+ Kg6 22. Qg3+ Rg5 23. Qe3 Re8
$19 {Quparadze-Tregubov, Doha 2016.}) (9. Bd3 d5 $1 10. Nxc6 (10. Ba3 Qa5 11.
Qc1 (11. Nb5 a6 12. Nd6+ Nxd6 13. Bxd6 Qd8 14. Ba3 e5 15. Qh5 Be6 $15 {
Yeletsky-Lintchevski, St Petersburg 2014.}) 11... Nxc3 12. Nb3 Qc7 13. Re1 f6
$132 {[%cal Yd5d4,Ye8f7]}) 10... bxc6 11. Ba3 (11. Bxe4 dxe4 12. Qxd8+ (12. Qg4
O-O 13. Qxe4 Qd5 $15 {Petrov-Kulaots, Viljandi 2017.}) 12... Kxd8 13. Rd1+ Ke7
14. Ba3+ Kf6 {is OK for Black in Ashwin-Sutovsky, Caleta 2014.}) 11... c5 (
11... Nxc3 $2 12. Qg4 $1) 12. Bxe4 dxe4 13. Bxc5 Ba6 14. Re1 Qxd1 15. Raxd1 Rc8
16. Bb4 Bb7 17. Rd6 Bc6 18. h4 O-O 19. Rxc6 Rxc6 20. Bxf8 Kxf8 21. Rxe4 Rxc3
22. Ra4 Rxc2 23. Rxa7 h5 $11 {Rublevsky-Tregubov, Loo 2014.}) (9. Nxc6 dxc6 $1
(9... bxc6 $6 10. Qd4 $1) 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. Bf3 Nf6 $11) 9... d5 10. Ba3 Qa5 (
10... f5 $6 {is too optimistic:} 11. f3 Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Nf6 13. c4 $36 {and
White seized the initiative in Hou-Zhang, Xinghua Jiangsu 2009.}) 11. Nb5 (11.
c4 $2 Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Qxa3 $19) (11. Bb2 O-O $15) 11... a6 12. Nd6+ Nxd6 13. Bxd6
Ne7 $1 (13... Qd8 $2 {wastes a valuable tempo, which was nicely used by White
in the following miniature:} 14. Qg3 $1 Ne7 15. Bd3 Ng6 (15... O-O 16. Bxh7+ $1
Kxh7 17. Qh4+ Kg8 18. Bxe7 $18) 16. Rfe1 Bd7 17. c4 dxc4 18. Be4 Bc6 19. Bxc6+
bxc6 20. Rad1 Ra7 21. Bc5 Rd7 22. Rb1 Qh4 23. Rb8+ Rd8 24. Rd1 {1-0
Nisipeanu-Schneider, Germany 2010.}) 14. Bxe7 (14. c4 $6 Nf5 $1 15. Bf4 dxc4
16. Qxc4 Bd7 {and Black could start enjoying his extra pawn in Riff-Nataf,
Mulhouse 2011.}) (14. Qg3 $2 {is met by} Nf5 $1) (14. Rfe1 Qd8 15. Ba3 (15. Qg3
$2 {again fails to} Nf5 $1 $19) 15... b5 $1 {followed by castling kingside and
Black is more than fine, but not the immediate} (15... O-O $6 {in view of} 16.
c4 $1 {when White retains some pressure.})) 14... Kxe7 15. Qg3 g6 $132 {
[%cal Yf7f6,Ye7f7,Yc8d7] The position remains sharp, but Black's king is
relatively safe as White no longer has his bishop exploiting the weakened
dark-squares.} *

