1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4
4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. a3 {White is ready to give up a tempo just to stop
the annoying move ...Bb4 and accepts a possible transposition to a
Scheveningen setup, where the move a2-a3 is often quite useful.} Be7 {I like
this move as best for Black, not touching the d-pawn too early as in various
lines Black aims to play ...d7-d5 in one go.} ({The immediate attempt to take
advantage of White's last anti-developing move} 6... d5 $6 {has been played
here as well, though after} 7. Bb5 Bd7 8. exd5 exd5 ({Also after} 8... Nxd4 {
Black fails to equalize} 9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 10. Qxd4 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Qxd5 12. Qxd5
exd5 13. Be3 $16 {with a risk-free advantage for White in Alekseev-Malakhov, I
Tallinn 2016.}) 9. O-O Be7 10. Re1 $14 {and White has a pleasant edge in
Navara-Krasenkow, Drancy 2016.}) 7. Nxc6 (7. Be3 O-O (7... d5 $6 {is again
premature, in view of} 8. Bb5 $1 $14) 8. Be2 (8. f4 e5 $5) 8... d5 9. exd5 Nxd5
10. Nxd5 Qxd5 {see 7.Be2.}) (7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O d5 {ensures full equality:} 9.
exd5 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 Qxd5 11. Be3 (11. Nxc6 Qxc6 12. Bf3 Qc7 $11 {and next Black
brings his bishop to c6.}) 11... Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Qxd4 13. Bxd4 Rd8 (13... Bd7 14.
Bf3 Bc6 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. Rfd1 Rfd8 17. Kf1 f6 18. Be3 a6 19. Ke2 e5 $11 {
Chigaev-Korobov, Skopje 2019.}) 14. Rad1 (14. Rfd1 Bd7 15. a4 Bc6 16. a5 a6 17.
Bb6 Rxd1+ 18. Rxd1 Rc8 19. f4 h6 20. g3 f5 21. c3 {½-½ Cruzado Dueñas-Neto,
ICCF 2017.}) 14... Bd7 15. Bf3 Bc6 16. Bxc6 bxc6 17. Be3 a6 $11 {Van Foreest,
J-Vidit, Riadh blitz 2017. It may seem as if White has a better pawn structure
on the queenside, but there's no chance targetting those pawn weaknesses.}) (7.
f4 {[%cal Yd4f3]} O-O (7... d5 8. e5 Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Nd7 10. Be3 $14 {as seen in
Tischbierek-Gauglitz, Salzwedel 1982 leads to a French type of structure which
I rather avoid with Black.}) (7... d6 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bd3 a6 10. O-O b5 11. b4 a5
12. Rb1 axb4 13. axb4 d5 14. e5 Ne8 15. Nxb5 Ba6 16. Nbd4 Nxb4 17. Bxa6 Rxa6
18. f5 $40 {and White obtained a very dangerous attack in Anand-Giri, Saint
Louis 2019.}) 8. Nf3 ({In case of} 8. Be3 {Black has a couple of options, but
I think} e5 $5 {is quite interesting and leads to comfortable play for Black:}
9. Nxc6 (9. fxe5 Nxe5 10. Nf3 (10. Be2 d5 $1 $132) 10... d6 (10... Nfg4 $5) 11.
Be2 Be6 {with equal chances in Alikulov-Zakaryan, Moscow 2018.}) 9... dxc6 10.
f5 Qxd1+ 11. Rxd1 b5 12. Bd3 a5 {is unproblematic for Black in
Schmaltz-Nekrasov, Baden 2017.}) (8. e5 $6 Nd5 $1 9. Nxd5 exd5 10. Nf3 d6 11.
Qxd5 (11. exd6 $2 Bxd6 12. Bd3 Re8+ 13. Kf2 Bc5+ 14. Kg3 Qf6 $17 {[%csl Rg3]
Lanc-Pacher, Slovakia 2009.}) 11... Be6 {gives Black a huge lead in
development and good chances of retaining the pawn with interest.}) 8... d5 9.
e5 Nd7 (9... Ng4 $5 10. Bd3 Qb6 11. Qe2 f6 12. h3 Nh6 $132 {Baklanov-Dutra
Neto, LSS email 2010.}) 10. Be3 a6 11. Bd3 f6 12. exf6 Bxf6 $132 {with
excellent play for Black in Suarez Uriel-Xu, Roquetas de Mar 2019.}) (7. Bf4
O-O 8. Nxc6 (8. e5 Ne8 $132 {[%cal Yf7f6]}) 8... bxc6 9. Bd3 d5 10. O-O Nd7 11.
Re1 d4 12. Nb1 e5 13. Bg3 Bh4 $1 {and Black is very comfortable in
Sasikiran-Vocaturo, Porto Carras 2018. After the exchange of dark-squared
bishops he enjoys a very pleasant space advantage.}) 7... bxc6 8. e5 Nd5 9. Qg4
(9. Ne4 Qc7 10. f4 f5 $5 (10... Qb6 {is likely to transpose to Main Line with
10.a3 (Chapter 7).}) 11. Nd6+ (11. exf6 Nxf6 {is unproblematic for Black.})
11... Bxd6 12. exd6 Qb8 {was seen in Naiditsch-Kovalenko, Germany 2019, and now
} ({Interesting is} 12... Qb6 $5 13. c4 Nf6 14. b4 a5 15. c5 Qb8 {and having
provoked White to expand on the queenside also gives Black certain counterplay.
} 16. Bb2 axb4 (16... O-O $5 {[%cal Yc8a6] intending Ba6 is probably playable
as well.}) 17. Bxf6 gxf6 18. Qh5+ Kf8 19. Be2 Ba6 20. Qh6+ Kg8 {and it seems
White should give a perpetual.}) 13. c4 Nf6 {deserves further investigation.})
(9. Nxd5 cxd5 {is harmless.}) 9... g6 ({I think this weakening move is
playable, so no need to give up the right to castle with} 9... Kf8 $5 {
although this might also be possible.}) (9... O-O $6 10. Bh6 {cost an
exchange.}) 10. Qg3 (10. Ne4 $6 {was seen in Short-Alfaya Marcelo, Madrid 2016
and now} f5 $1 11. exf6 Nxf6 12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 $132 {[%cal Yd7d5,Ye6e5]}) 10...
Rb8 (10... f5 {was played in Zelcic-Nestorenko, Katowice 2017 and now} 11. exf6
Nxf6 12. Be2 $14) (10... d6 $5 {looks OK.}) (10... Qc7 $6 11. Ne4 $1 f5 {
isn't great, in view of} 12. Nd6+ $1 {(one advantage to have the queen on g3!)}
) (10... Qb6 {with the idea of Ba6 also comes into consideration.}) 11. Ne4 $1
Qa5+ 12. Bd2 Qa4 13. Bd3 Ba6 {was played in Lupulescu-Kovalenko,
Khanty-Mansiysk 2019 and here White's play can be improved with} (13... Rxb2 $2
14. c4 Nb6 15. Bc3 Rb3 16. O-O $16 {[%csl Ra4,Rb3]} (16. Bc2 $6 Rxc3 17. Qxc3
Qxc4 $44)) 14. Qg4 $1 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Yg4a4]} Kd8 15. Bxa6 Qxa6 16. b3 $16 *

