1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4.
Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Ndb5 Bc5 $5 ({The third popular continuation, but it
fits well with the dynamical character of other variations in this opening
repertoire. A more solid alternative is} 6... Bb4 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 d5 9.
exd5 exd5 10. Bd3 $14 {but in my opinion, White has slightly more pleasant
prospects without risking too much.}) ({The main continuation here is} 6... d6
7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {with a transposition to the Main Lines of the Sveshnikov. In
fact, this is actually quite a popular move-order for Sveshnikov players, as
it rules out the possibility for White to go for the fashionable 7.Nd5 which
was played by Caruana against Carlsen in their World Championship match in
2018.}) 7. Bf4 ({The main line. Another critical branch is} 7. Nd6+ Ke7 8. Bf4
(8. Nxc8+ $6 Rxc8 9. Bd3 Qc7 {gives Black comfortably play:} 10. O-O {and here
several moves have been tried, but I quite like} h5 $5 11. Bg5 (11. h4 $4 Ng4
12. g3 Qxg3+ {0-1 Karykowska-Heberla, Zgierz 2018.}) (11. h3 $4 {also runs into
} Ng4 $1) 11... Kf8 12. Bh4 (12. Bxf6 gxf6 {with excellent play on the
dark-squares for Black.}) (12. Qd2 Ng4 13. Bf4 {was seen in Arakhamia
Grant-Movileanu, Caleta 2019, but here Black's play can be improved with} Bd6
$1 14. Bxd6+ (14. Nb5 $2 Bxf4 $19) 14... Qxd6 15. f4 g5 $1 $36) 12... Ne5 13.
Na4 Neg4 14. Bg3 Bd6 15. Bxd6+ Qxd6 {and White is already lost in Poetz-Dreev,
Trieste 2019.}) 8... e5 $1 (8... Qb6 $2 {is bad, in view of} 9. Qd2 $1 Qxb2 (
9... Bxf2+ 10. Qxf2 Qxb2 11. Qc5 Qxa1+ 12. Kd2 $18 {with a crushing attack for
White.}) 10. Rb1 Qa3 11. Nc4 Qa6 12. Ne5 Qa3 13. Rb3 Qa5 14. Nxc6+ dxc6 15.
Nd5+ {wins the queen.}) 9. Nf5+ ({Once again,} 9. Nxc8+ {helps Black to
untangle, e.g.} Rxc8 10. Bg5 Bb4 11. Qd2 (11. Bd3 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 h6 13. Bxf6+
gxf6 {and Black doesn't have any problems.}) 11... Bxc3 12. bxc3 (12. Qxc3 {
is met by} Nd4 $1 13. Qb4+ d6 14. Bd3 Nxc2+ 15. Bxc2 Rxc2 16. Qxb7+ Qd7 $17 {
with a clear advantage for Black in Szylar-Raetsky, Cappelle-la-Grande 2005.})
12... Qc7 {intending Nd8-e6 with good play for Black.}) 9... Kf8 10. Bg5 (10.
Be3 Bb4 $1 (10... Bxe3 $2 11. Qd6+ Kg8 12. Nxe3 $16 {favors White in
Dourerassou-Bellon Lopez, Lund 2019.}) 11. Nd6 (11. Qf3 $2 {is strongly met by}
d5 $1) (11. a3 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 d5 {is fine for Black.}) (11. Bc4 $6 d5 $1 12.
Bxd5 Nxd5 13. Qxd5 Qxd5 14. exd5 Bxf5 15. dxc6 bxc6 $11 {
Gavrilakis-Mastrovasilis,A Kallithea 2009.}) 11... Qe7 12. Nf5 (12. Nxc8 $6
Rxc8 {looks wonderful for Black in Ilyuchyk-Badelka, Minsk 2017.}) 12... Qd8
$11 {with a repetition of moves.}) 10... d6 (10... Bb4 11. Ne3 $1 Qa5 (11... h6
12. Bxf6 Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 Qxf6 14. Bc4 d6 15. O-O $14 {Salgado Lopez-Chernov,
Haguenau 2013.}) 12. Nc4 Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 Qxc3+ 14. Bd2 Qd4 15. f3 Kg8 16. c3 Qc5
17. Bc1 {[%cal Yc1a3]} Qe7 18. Ba3 d6 19. Qxd6 Qe8 20. Qc7 Qd7 21. Qxd7 ({
Inferior is} 21. Bd6 $2 Qe6 $1 22. Nxe5 Ne8 23. Nxc6 Nxc7 24. Ne7+ Kf8 25. Nf5+
{½-½ Huschenbeth-Chernov, Neustadt an der Weinstrasse 2017.}) 21... Bxd7 22.
Kf2 $16 {with a clear advantage for White.}) (10... h6 $5 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. Nd5
Qd8 13. c3 g6 14. Nfe3 a6 (14... d6 15. Qd2 Be6 16. g3 Kg7 17. h4 Ne7 {with
about equal chances in Quesada Perez-El Debs, Campinas 2013.}) 15. Bc4 Kg7 16.
O-O d6 17. Kh1 Rf8 {with a normal position in Triapishko-Pridorozhni, Sochi
2019, where White may be just somewhat better.}) 11. Ne3 (11. Bc4 Be6 12. Bb3
h6 13. Bxf6 (13. Bh4 $6 {fails to} g5 14. Bg3 Nxe4 $1) 13... Qxf6 14. Ne3 g6
15. O-O Kg7 16. Ncd5 Qd8 $132 {is OK for Black in Jansa-Jasny, Czech Republic
2016.}) (11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. Nd5 Qg6 (12... Qd8 13. c3 Bxf5 14. exf5 Ne7 15. Nxe7
Qxe7 16. Qd5 g6 $132 {Hovhannisyan,R-Kabanov, St Petersburg 2012.}) 13. Qf3 Be6
14. Bd3 Nb4 15. Nxb4 Bxb4+ 16. c3 Bc5 17. O-O Qf6 18. Rfd1 Rd8 $132 {
Kanmazalp-Heberla, Cappelle-la-Grande 2014.}) 11... h6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Ncd5
Qd8 14. c3 Be6 15. b4 Bxe3 16. Nxe3 Qc7 17. Be2 g6 18. O-O {was played in
Schroeder-Vocaturo, Germany 2018 and now} Ne7 $132 {followed by Kg7 with
reasonable play for Black.}) (7. Be3 $6 {is harmless:} Bxe3 8. Nd6+ Ke7 9. fxe3
Qc7 $1 {and Black's already better.} 10. Ndb5 (10. Ncb5 Qb6 11. Qd2 Ng4 $15) (
10. Nc4 a6 11. a4 Rd8 {and Black gets in ...d7-d5.}) 10... Qe5 $1 11. Qd2 a6
12. Nd4 b5 13. O-O-O Bb7 $17 {Wells-Hall, Germany 1999.}) 7... O-O 8. Bc7 ({
Not allowing the queen to come to b6. Less precise is} 8. Bd6 {in view of} Qb6
$1 9. Bxc5 (9. Bxf8 $4 Bxf2+ 10. Kd2 Qe3#) 9... Qxc5 10. Qd6 Qb6 $1 (10... Qxd6
$2 11. Nxd6 $16 {is excellent for White.}) 11. Qc7 (11. Rb1 $2 a6 12. Na3 {
was seen in Bologan-Safarli, Khanty-Mansiysk 2013, but then Black should go for
} Qa7 {intending ...b7-b5 with excellent play.}) (11. Qd2 d5 $1 12. exd5 exd5
13. O-O-O Bf5 $132 {[%cal Ya8c8] with sharp play.} (13... Rd8 14. Na4 (14. Nd4
$2 Ne4 $1 {went completely wrong for White in Kosteniuk-Muzychuk,M Moscow 2010.
}) 14... Qa6 15. b3 $14)) (11. a4 Ne8 $1 (11... a6 $5 12. a5 axb5 13. axb6
Rxa1+ 14. Nd1 Nxe4 15. Qd3 d5 16. Be2 Bd7 $44)) 11... Qc5 12. Qd6 $11 {and
many games have ended in a draw this way.}) (8. e5 a6 $1 (8... Ne8 {has been
played here as well, though the following game should be a warning signal for
Black players:} 9. Ne4 Be7 10. c3 a6 11. Nbd6 Bxd6 12. Nxd6 Qc7 13. Bd3 Nxd6
14. exd6 Qd8 15. Qh5 f5 16. g4 b5 17. O-O-O Qf6 18. gxf5 exf5 19. Bc2 Na5 20.
Rhg1 Bb7 21. Rde1 Qf7 22. Qh6 Be4 23. Rxe4 fxe4 24. Be5 g6 25. Bxe4 {1-0
Tsydypov-Pridorozhni, Kazan 2017.}) 9. Nd6 (9. exf6 Qxf6 $15 {and Black
regains the piece next move.}) 9... Ne8 $5 (9... Bxd6 $2 {is terrible mistake.
The following game shows how quickly things can wrong for Black:} 10. Qxd6 Qb6
$4 11. exf6 Qxb2 12. Kd2 Qxa1 13. Bh6 $1 $18 {with a crushing attack for White
in Dubov-Basso, Skopje 2019.}) 10. Nce4 (10. Nde4 $2 {is just bad, because
after} Bd4 $1 11. Qh5 {Black could have obtained a decisive advantage in
Hoolt-Schleining, Germany 2013 by means of} f6 $1 $19 {and White's position
falls apart.}) 10... Bd4 11. Nxe8 Rxe8 12. c3 (12. Nd6 $2 {was seen in
Warszawski-Heberla, Warsaw 2009, but now why not the simple} Bxb2 $1) 12...
Bxe5 13. Bxe5 Nxe5 14. Nd6 Rf8 {with some compensation for the pawn, but Black
is OK.}) 8... Qe7 9. Bd6 Bxd6 10. Qxd6 (10. Nxd6 {has been seen here as well,
but isn't too problematic as with moves a6 and Ne8 Black releases himself.})
10... Qd8 11. O-O-O (11. Qc7 $6 {can be answered with} d5 $1 12. exd5 exd5 13.
Qxd8 Rxd8 14. Ne2 (14. O-O-O $6 d4 $1 15. Ne2 (15. Nb1 $2 Ne4 $19 {Pavlidis,
A-Heberla, Katowice 2017.}) 15... Ne4 $1 {favors Black.}) 14... a6 ({I also
had a look at the more active} 14... d4 15. Rd1 d3 (15... Be6 16. Nbxd4 (16. a3
Rd7 17. Nbxd4 Rad8 18. c3 Bc4 $11) 16... Bxa2 17. Nxc6 bxc6 18. Rxd8+ Rxd8 19.
Nc3 $14) 16. Rxd3 Bf5 (16... Rxd3 17. cxd3 Bf5 (17... Bd7 $14) 18. Ned4 (18.
Ng3 $5) 18... Nxd4 19. Nxd4 Bg6 20. Be2 Rd8 $11 {and Black regains the pawn in
Tate-Dobrowolski, Pardubice 2019.}) 17. Rxd8+ Rxd8 18. c3 $14) 15. Nbd4 Re8 $11
{[%csl Re2,Rf1,Rh1] seems OK for Black. The isolated pawn is always a source
of problems for Black, but on the other hand, White's configuration of pieces
on the kingside doesn't enable him to become very active.}) (11. Nc7 {seems
less critical to me than 11.0-0-0.} Rb8 (11... Ne8 $6 {looks strategically
dangerous for Black because after} 12. Nxe8 Rxe8 13. Bb5 $5 $16 {White is
about to take on c6, leaving Black with some problems covering the
dark-squares.}) 12. Be2 (12. O-O-O b5 (12... a6 $5 13. Be2 b5 {is perhaps
simpler.}) 13. Bxb5 Rb7 (13... Rb6 $5 {is worth checking.}) (13... Bb7 $2 14.
Be2 Rc8 15. N7b5 Qb6 16. Qf4 d5 17. exd5 exd5 18. Nd4 Rfe8 19. Bb5 Ne4 20. Bxc6
Nxc3 21. Bxe8 Nxa2+ 22. Kb1 Nc3+ 23. Kc1 Na2+ {and now in Aghayev-Muzychuk,A
Baku 2013, White accepted the repetition, but instead} 24. Kd2 Qb4+ 25. Ke3
Rxe8+ 26. Kf3 $18 {would have given a decisive advantage.}) 14. Bxc6 Rxc7 15.
Ba4 Rxc3 16. bxc3 Nxe4 17. Qd4 {and it's hard to believe that Black got
sufficient compensation for the material in Abelguzin-Botoyan, Ufa 2016.})
12... b5 13. e5 (13. N7xb5 a6 $1 ({Inferior is} 13... Qb6 $2 14. Rb1 $1 Ba6 15.
a4 Rfc8 16. Bd3 Ne8 17. Qg3 Bxb5 18. axb5 Nd4 19. O-O $16 {Fedorov-Kabanov,
Samara 2012.}) 14. Nd4 Nxd4 15. Qxd4 Rxb2 16. O-O (16. e5 $6 Qa5 $1 {is a nice
counterattack, as} 17. exf6 Rxc2 {is fine for Black.}) 16... d6 $11 {and Black
is fine.}) 13... Ne8 $5 ({More popular is} 13... b4 $6 {which leads to sharper
play, but objectively speaking I don't really trust it:} 14. exf6 bxc3 15. fxg7
Kxg7 16. Qg3+ (16. b3 $5 Qf6 17. Rd1 Nb4 (17... Bb7 $5 {[%cal Yc6e7,Yf8g8]})
18. O-O Rb6 19. Qc5 Bb7 $2 (19... Nxc2 20. Rd3 d6 21. Qh5 Rb4 (21... Nb4 $4 22.
Rf3 Qe5 23. Ne8+ Kh8 24. Qh6 {1-0 Utiatskaja-Asatryan, Batumi 2018.}) 22. Rg3+
Kh8 {and the game goes on!}) 20. Rxd7 Rc8 21. Bh5 Nd5 22. Nxd5 exd5 23. Qe3 $18
{Van Kampen-Wiersma, Hoogeveen 2012.}) 16... Kh8 17. Qxc3+ e5 18. Nb5 $1 (18.
Nd5 Nd4 $132 {[%cal Yc8b7] Gaponenko-Muzychuk,M Moscow 2010.}) 18... Qf6 (18...
Rb6 19. O-O-O d5 {Fuchs-Muzychuk, M Riga 2017.} 20. f4 $1 $16) 19. Qa3 $1 {
followed by castling queenside, White retains the better prospects with an
extra pawn.}) 14. Nxe8 Rxe8 15. O-O b4 16. Ne4 Rb6 17. f4 (17. a3 $5 bxa3 18.
Rxa3 {with ideas like Rg3/Nf6 in the air, looks quite dangerous}) 17... Ne7 $5
{I slightly prefer White, but it's a fighting position.} (17... Ba6 18. Bxa6
Rxa6 $16 {[%csl Rd7] Aghayev-Basso, Brixen Bressanone 2019.})) (11. Be2 {
isn't dangerous for Black:} a6 12. Nc7 (12. Nd4) 12... Ra7 13. e5 Nxe5 14. Qxe5
b6 15. N7d5 $6 (15. Nxe6 fxe6 $132) 15... Nxd5 16. Nxd5 exd5 17. O-O-O (17.
Qxd5 Bb7 {and Black seizes the initiative.}) 17... Re8 18. Qh5 g6 19. Qf3 d6
20. Rd2 Rae7 $15 {and Black's better in Baron-Dubov, Douglas 2019.}) 11... a6
12. Nd4 Ne7 $5 ({A relatively new approach. Black's main continuation is} 12...
Qb6 {but then} 13. Nxc6 $5 {seems to give White a slightly favourable
pawn structure (with a bad bishop on c8 as a result). Hence, top players like
Navara and Dreev have tried this move which avoids that structure. The ensuing
positions are new and certainly deserve further investigation.}) 13. h4 (13.
Qg3 b5 ({What about} 13... d5 $5 14. e5 Nd7 15. f4 {with a structure you
normally see in the Steinitz Variation of the French. Looks playable for Black
too.}) 14. e5 Nfd5 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Nf5 exf5 17. Rxd5 Qa5 (17... Bb7 $5) 18.
a3 Bb7 19. Rd4 (19. Rxd7 $6 Rad8 $1 {looks dangerous.} 20. Rxb7 $2 Qe1#) 19...
Rae8 20. f4 Re6 21. Bd3 Rg6 {and now in Nevednichy-Navara, Patras 2019.} 22.
Qe3 Rxg2 23. Bxf5 $16 {followed by Rhd1, White seems to be in control.}) (13.
g4 b5 14. g5 Ne8 15. Qg3 Bb7 (15... b4 $5) 16. Bg2 Rc8 17. a3 {and now
Volokitin-Polivanov, Minsk 2017, doesn't seem to be too bad for Black if he
goes for} Qc7 {and soon ...f7-f6 (or even ...f7-f5).}) (13. e5 {as played in
Suran-Jurcik, Czech Republic 2018 and now} Ne8 $132 {seems perfectly playable
for Black.}) 13... b5 14. f3 (14. h5 Ne8 15. Qb4 (15. Qh2 b4 $1) 15... Bb7 (
15... h6 {invites White to go for} 16. g4 $5) 16. h6 g6 17. a4 Nc6 18. Qc5 bxa4
19. Nxa4 Rc8 20. Kb1 (20. f3 $14 {[%csl Ge4]}) 20... Nb8 $1 {[%csl Re4] was
missed by White in Sarana-Dreev, Izhevsk 2019.}) 14... Bb7 (14... Ne8 $5) 15.
Nb3 Nc8 16. Qd4 Qc7 17. Bd3 d6 $132 {with mutual chances in Ladron de Guevara
Pinto-Basso, Brixen Bressanone 2019.} *

