1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4.
Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. e5 {This is White's sharpest and most
principled way of challenging Black.} Nd5 8. Ne4 (8. Nxd5 cxd5 {isn't
problematic, e.g.} 9. Bd3 Qc7 (9... Ba6 $5 $11 {is perhaps even a simpler
option, to get rid of the bad bishop as soon as possible.} 10. Bxa6 Qa5+) 10.
f4 (10. Bf4 Rb8 11. O-O (11. b3 $2 Bb4+) 11... Rxb2 12. Re1 g6 13. h4 h5 14.
Qf3 Bg7 $15 {Fedorchuk-Hasangatin, Chrudim 2003.}) 10... Bc5 11. Qe2 Rb8 12. c3
O-O {with excellent play for Black in Jovanovic-Saric, Otocac 2010.}) 8... f5 (
{Besides the Main Line} 8... Qc7 {which will be discussed in the next chapters,
Black has a couple of other options. There are all leading to interesting play,
but somehow they don't really appeal to me as Black neither obtains full
equality nor gets sufficient counterplay to pose White some practical problems.
Hence, it's not surprising that 8...Qc7 has the preference of the majority of
top players.}) (8... Bb7 9. Be2 c5 10. O-O Qc7 11. Nd6+ (11. c4 Ne3 12. Nd6+
Bxd6 13. exd6 Qc6 14. Bf3 Nxd1 15. Bxc6 Bxc6 16. Rxd1 O-O {was first played in
Shirov-Kramnik, Frankfurt 2000, but has a very drawish reputation.}) 11... Bxd6
12. exd6 Qc6 (12... Qxd6 $2 13. c4 {wins a piece.}) 13. f3 c4 14. Qd4 O-O 15.
Bxc4 $14 {was played a couple of times by Leko and Grischuk at the beginning
of the century, but the general opinion is that White is better, thanks to his
bishop pair in combination with the possibility to advance on the queenside.
Recently this line was tried in Vachier Lagrave-Kovalenko, Khanty-Mansiysk
2019, but that game didn't really change the verdict.}) 9. exf6 Nxf6 10. Nd6+
Bxd6 11. Qxd6 Ba6 (11... Qe7 12. Bf4 $1 $16) (11... Qb6 12. Bd3 (12. c3 $2
Qxf2+ $1) 12... c5 13. Bf4 Bb7 (13... Qxb2 14. O-O) 14. O-O Rc8 15. c4 Qxd6 (
15... Rc6 16. Qe5 O-O 17. Rfe1 Bc8 18. Qc3 d6 19. Rad1 Qd8 20. Bc2 $16 {
Parligras-Barrientos Chavarriaga, Solsona 2005.}) 16. Bxd6 Rc6 17. Be5 {
with a risk-free advantage for White in Illescas Cordoba-Cifuentes Parada,
Seville 2004.}) 12. Bxa6 Qa5+ 13. Bd2 Qxa6 14. f3 $1 (14. Bb4 {is the most
common move, but after} O-O-O {things are less clear.}) 14... Kf7 15. a3 Rhe8
16. O-O-O Rab8 17. Bc3 Rb7 18. Rhe1 $16 {Dominguez Perez-Escobar Forero,
Khanty-Mansiysk 2019.} *

