1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4.
Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. e5 (7. Bd3 {This structure is well-known
from 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 e6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.Bd3, but
compared with that line Black has omitted the move ...a7-a6.} d5 8. O-O Be7 9.
Qf3 O-O 10. Re1 a5 {intending to swap light-squared bishops.} 11. exd5 (11. Bg5
Ba6 12. Bxa6 Rxa6 $132 {Gazel Pereira-Barbosa, Pocos de Caldas 2018.}) 11...
exd5 ({The ensuing pawn structure is reminiscent of the Scotch Four Knight (1.
e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.d4 exd4 5.Nxd4), but Black is absolutely fine.
A more ambitious player may prefer} 11... cxd5 $5) 12. h3 Bd6 13. Ne2 Re8 14. Bg5
Be5 {with about equal play in Liang-Lenderman, Saint Louis 2019.}) 7... Nd5 8.
Ne4 Qc7 9. f4 (9. Nd6+ $6 Bxd6 10. exd6 Qxd6 11. c4 {doesn't win a piece, in
view of} Qe5+ $1) 9... Qb6 ({The point of Black's play as he intends to take
advantage of the dark-squares. Various other moves, including} 9... Qa5+) (9...
f5) (9... Rb8 {have been tried here, but the text is by far the most popular
and hence the Main Line for our repertoire.}) 10. Bd3 (10. c4 {Main Line and
will be examined in the next chapters. We will focus on 10...Bb4, but it's
worth mentioning that} Ne3 {is another critical line.}) (10. a3 f5 $5 ({
A solid option is} 10... Ne3 11. Qd3 Nxf1 12. Rxf1 Ba6 13. c4 Qa5+ 14. Ke2 (14.
Bd2 Qd5 $1 $132) 14... f5 15. Nd6+ (15. exf6 $2 d5 $1) 15... Bxd6 16. exd6 {
I rate White's chances (opposite-coloured bishop, space, initiative etc.)
higher in this position.}) (10... Be7 11. c4 Ne3 12. Qd3 Nxf1 13. Rxf1 c5 $132
{Santarius-Nakar, Madison 2017.}) 11. exf6 Nxf6 12. Nxf6+ gxf6 13. Qh5+ Kd8 {
led to very sharp play in Adams-Zhou, Sheffield 2011 where anything could
happen. This would be my pick!}) 10... Be7 ({I slightly prefer this move to} 
10... Ba6 {which has a more solid reputation and should be playable too:} 11.
Bxa6 Qxa6 12. Qe2 Qxe2+ 13. Kxe2 f5 14. Nf2 (14. exf6 Nxf6 15. Nxf6+ gxf6 $132)
14... d6 (14... Rb8 15. c4 Nb4 16. b3 Bc5 17. Rd1 Ke7 18. Nd3 Nxd3 19. Rxd3 Rb7
$11 {with about equality in De la Villa Garcia-Nunn, Leon 1997.}) 15. Nd3 (15.
exd6 Bxd6 16. Nd3 a5 17. c4 Nb4 $132 {Wacker-Banusz, Tegernsee 2018.}) 15...
dxe5 16. Nxe5 Bd6 17. c4 Bxe5 18. fxe5 $14 {favors White.}) (10... f5 11. exf6
Nxf6 12. Nxf6+ gxf6 13. Qh5+ Kd8 14. Bd2 {[%csl Rd8] feels a bit shaky for
Black.}) 11. Qe2 (11. c4 $6 f5 12. exf6 Nxf6 {is fine for Black. The following
game illustrates well the dangers White is facing when not opting for the main
lines:} 13. Qc2 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 Ba6 15. Bd2 Bf6 16. Rb1 d5 17. Bxh7 O-O-O {
and White is already lost:} 18. b3 Qd4 19. Bd3 dxc4 20. Bxc4 Bxc4 21. bxc4 Bh4+
22. Kd1 Qxf4 23. Kc1 Rxd2 24. Qxd2 Qxc4+ 25. Qc2 Qf4+ 26. Qd2 Qe5 27. Qd3 Qc5+
28. Qc2 Bg5+ 29. Kb2 Bf6+ 30. Kc1 Qe3+ 31. Qd2 Qa3+ {0-1 Ye-Ivanchuk, Manila
1992.}) 11... f5 12. exf6 Nxf6 13. Nxf6+ Bxf6 14. c3 (14. Rb1 Bb7 15. Be3 Bd4
$132) 14... Rb8 15. Rb1 O-O 16. Be3 (16. Qe3 c5 {[%cal Yc8a6,Yd7d5] followed
by ...Ba6 with excellent play for Black.}) 16... Bxc3+ 17. bxc3 Qxb1+ 18. Bxb1
Rxb1+ 19. Kf2 Rxh1 $132 *

