Bxf5 32. Bxf5 Rxf5+ 33. Qxf5 Rxd6 $132) 31... gxf6 32. Qxc5 Qe5 33. Rxb6 Qxh2+
34. Ke1 Rd8 (34... Qg3+ $11) 35. Rxf6 Qg3+ 36. Bf2 Qc3+ 37. Kf1 Rd1+ $3 {
(beautiful drawing mechanism)} 38. Bxd1 Qh3+ 39. Ke1 Qc3+ 40. Kf1 {½-½
Mroczek-Zawadka, ICCF 2017.}) 24... Rcc8 $1 25. Qg4 g6 $1 {needs to be further
investigated. I believe 23...Qb8 is a simpler option for Black.}) 24. Bg4 Nxf4+
25. Bxf4 Rd8 $1 26. Qf5 (26. Rg3 Rxd7 27. Bxd7 Qc7 28. Bxc6 Qxc6 29. Rxd6 Qe4+
30. Re3 Qxc4+ 31. Ke1 Kg8 $11) 26... Rf8 27. Qd7 {½-½ Godart-Fischer, ICCF
email 2015.}) 23... Rb6 (23... Bc8 $2 {is just bad for Black, because of} 24.
Qd5 Bxh3 25. Qxc6 Bg4+ 26. Ke1 Bxd1 27. Kxd1 $18) 24. b3 Ra6 (24... d5 $2 {
is desirable, but runs into} 25. Qd7 $1 Qb8 26. Bxc5 Nxf4+ 27. Kd2 Rd8 28. Qf5
$1 dxc4+ 29. Kc3 {and White is dominating the centre of the board.}) 25. Rd2 ({
This modest move, protecting the pawn on a2, has only been tried once in
a high-profile game. In fact, things are much more complicated as Wei Yi shows
in the following game as he launches a very spectacular queen sacrifice. In
the world of correspondence play, the experts have been more focused on} 25. Qd7
Qb8 {(Threatening ...Bc8)} (25... Rxa2+ $2 26. Rd2 Rxd2+ 27. Bxd2 Bg2 (27...
Qxd7 28. Bxd7 {is awful for Black.}) 28. Rf2 Bxh3 29. Qxh3 $16) 26. Qg4 Rxa2+ (
26... Qe8 $2 {enables White to consolidate in a very effective manner:} 27. Rd2
$1 g6 28. f5 Bc8 29. Qf3 Bxf5 30. Ke1 $1 Kg7 31. Re2 $1 Bxh3 32. Qxh3 Qc8 33.
Qg2 Qc6 34. Qg4 Re8 (34... Qc8 $2 35. Bd4+ cxd4 36. Re7+ Kg8 37. Rxf8+ Qxf8 38.
Qe6+ Kh8 39. Re8) 35. Kd1 Kg8 36. Bc1 $1 $18 {and soon the dark-squared bishop
appeared on the long diagonal with a devastating effect in Gonzaga
Grego-Bennborn, ICCF 2017.}) 27. Rd2 Rxd2+ 28. Bxd2 (28. Kxd2 Be4 29. f5 (29.
Qxh5 $2 Qxb3 {is bad.}) 29... d5 30. cxd5 Qxh2+ 31. Rf2 Qe5 32. Qxh5 Bxd5 {
and White's king is too exposed to use the extra piece.}) 28... Qe8+ 29. Kd1 (
29. Kf2 Nxf4 $1 30. Bxf4 h5 $1 (30... Qe4 $2 31. Kg3 $18) 31. gxh6 (31. Qh4 Qe4
32. Qxh5+ (32. Kg3 $4 g6 $1 {Zugzwang!}) 32... Kg8 33. Kg3 Rxf4 34. Rxf4 Qe1+
$11) 31... gxh6 {Suddenly it becomes clear that the white king can't go to the
g-file now.} 32. Qh4 Qg6 33. Ra1 {½-½ Camps-Flitsch, ICCF 2018.} (33. Ke3 $4
Qe4+ 34. Kd2 Qd4+ {and Black wins.}) 33... Qg5 $1 {is a simple idea to regain
the piece.} (33... Qc2+ $2 {isn't good, because of} 34. Kg1 Qg6+ 35. Bg3 $18))
29... Qe4 30. Qxh5 Qd3 31. f5 (31. Qe2 $2 Qxb3+ 32. Ke1 Qxh3 $19) 31... Qxb3+
32. Ke1 g6 $1 33. Qe2 (33. fxg6 Qb1+ 34. Ke2 Qe4+ $11) 33... Qxh3 34. Qe7 Qh4+
35. Rf2 (35. Kd1 Qg4+ $1) 35... Qe4+ 36. Qxe4 Bxe4 37. f6 Bd3 38. Bf4 (38. Bc3
h6 $11) 38... Re8+ 39. Kd2 Bxc4 40. Bxd6 Bf7 $11 {and soon a draw was agreed
in Tritt-Szerlak, ICCF 2019.}) 25... d5 $1 26. Qe5 (26. Qd7 Qb8 (26... Qxd7 $6
27. Bxd7 d4 28. Bg1 $14) 27. Bxc5 Bc8 28. Qe7 Rg8 29. Bxc8 Qxc8 30. Kd1 dxc4
31. bxc4 Rc6 $132 {is OK for Black.}) 26... Re8 27. cxd5 Rxe5 28. fxe5 Bxd5 29.
Bg2 Rxa2 $1 (29... c4 $2 {is already lost for Black:} 30. Bxd5 c3 31. Bb7 cxd2
32. Bxa6 Qe8 33. Bc4 g6 34. e6 {1-0 Wei Yi-Fier, Moscow 2019.}) 30. Bxd5 Rxd2+
31. Bxd2 Nf6 (31... Qxd5 $2 32. Rf8+ Qg8 33. Rxg8+ Kxg8 34. Kd3 $18) 32. gxf6 (
32. Bc4 Nd7 $1 (32... Ne4 $2 {leads to problems for the black king after} 33.
Be1 $1 h5 34. g6 $1) 33. Bc3 Nb6 34. Be6 g6 35. Rf7 Nd5 36. Bxd5 Qxd5 37. e6+
Kg8 38. Rg7+ Kf8 39. e7+ Ke8 40. Bf6 {and Black should give a perpetual.})
32... Qxd5 33. f7 Qe4+ 34. Be3 Qc2+ {with a perpetual check.} *

